  "name": "1 Corinthians 1:18–31",
  "localizedName": "1 Corinthians 1:18–31",
  "content": [
    {
      "tiptap": {
        "type": "doc",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "God’s "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108325",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "wisdom"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " is very different from what Paul called the wisdom of the "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108215",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "world"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": ". He was talking about "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108195",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "sin"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " and ways of thinking and acting that are based on sinful desires."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The wisdom of the world isn’t based on the ways of God. Paul showed how God works in ways that people don’t expect. He often works through things and people who are considered foolish and unimportant."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The greatest example of this is how Jesus was nailed to the "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "resourceReference",
                    "attrs": {
                      "resourceId": "108530",
                      "resourceType": "BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms"
                    }
                  }
                ],
                "text": "cross"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " and died. To those around Jesus, it looked like he had failed completely. But God worked powerfully through Jesus’ death. Through his death, Jesus set people free from the power of sin and death."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "On the cross, Jesus seemed weak and foolish. But in actual fact he was powerful and wise. Jesus’ followers mustn’t boast about their own wisdom or strength. Instead they must tell others about the wonderful works of the Lord."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ],
